http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/Officials-booked-on-charge-of-misuse-of-funds/article14002512.ece

Following a complaint by zilla panchayat deputy secretary Mukkanna Karigar, the Sadar Bazar police, Raichur, booked six officials of the Karnataka Rural Infrastructure Development Limited (KRIDL) on Thursday on the charge of misappropriating funds to the tune of Rs. 1.98 crore.The accused, Appaj, former executive engineer, Raichur; Abdul Rasheed, assistant executive engineer, Sindhanur; Syed Mobin, assistant executive engineer, Deodurg; Anil Patil, assistant engineer; Manvi, Basavaraj, assistant engineer, Deodurg and Shivaraj, junior engineer, Deodurg, were booked under Sections 409 (Criminal breach of trust by public servant), 420 (Cheating), 465 (Punishment for forgery), 468 (Forgery for purpose of cheating), 120B (Punishment of criminal conspiracy) of the Indian Penal Code. “We have arrested Abdul Rasheed and are collecting the whereabouts of others for taking into custody,” K.H. Dadavali, Sub-Inspector, attached to Sadar Bazar police station said. Mr. Karigar had said that Rs. 1.98 crore was released by the zilla panchayat in 2011-12 and 2012-13 for developing small irrigation tanks across the district and the amount was drawn by the accused without implementing the projects.In another similar case, the Deodurg police on Thursday, booked eight elected members of the Deodurg Town Municipal Council (TMC) and three government servants on the charges of misappropriating public funds meant for various social welfare programmes.The accused have been identified as Nagappa, vice president, Rangappa, Tayamma, Yashodhamma, Peerma Begum, Hemanna Rathod, Chandrashekhar, Venkatesh (all TMC members), Rajashekhar Patil, community organising officer, Shreepada Bhatt, chief officer (now at Saligram TMC, Udupi district) and Saroja Patil, chief officer (now Commissioner at Shahabad City Municipal Council, Kalaburagi district).Firoz Khan H., chief officer of Deodurg TMC, had alleged that the accused had misappropriated Rs. 3.15 lakh of public funds.